                <fr:title text="Bolza Problem">Bolza Problem</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
    Bolza problem is a fundamental formulation in the calculus of variations and optimal control that minimizes a cost functional consisting of both an integral term (running cost) and a terminal cost <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[J := \int _0^{t_f} L \big (\mathbf {x}(t), \mathbf {u}(t)\big ) dt + \Phi  \left ( \mathbf {x}(t_f) \right )]]></fr:tex> where state <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {x}(t)\in  \mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex>, control <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {u}(t)\in  \mathbb {R}^k]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L:\mathbb {R}^n \times  \mathbb {R}^k \to  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> is the running cost and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Phi :\mathbb {R}^n \to  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> is the terminal cost. The goal is to find the optimal control <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {u}^*(t)\in  \mathbb {R}^k]]></fr:tex> that minimizes this cost functional subject to the system dynamics and boundary conditions.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/boat/" title="Zihang Zeng" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/boat/" display-uri="boat" type="local">Zihang Zeng</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>22</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://boatnotabot.com/opt-6003/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>opt-6003</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/opt-6003/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="First-order Variation of the Bolza Functional">First-order Variation of the Bolza Functional</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
    To find the optimal control <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {u}]]></fr:tex>, we consider the first-order variation of the functional <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[J]]></fr:tex> with respect to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {u}]]></fr:tex>. By augmenting the cost functional with system dynamics <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\dot  \mathbf {x} = f(\mathbf {x}, \mathbf {u})]]></fr:tex> using the costate <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {p}]]></fr:tex>, we define:
</html:p>
                <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
    \frac {\partial  J}{\partial  \mathbf {u}} = \left ( \frac {\partial  f}{\partial  \mathbf {u}} \right )^\intercal  \mathbf {p} + \left ( \frac {\partial  L}{\partial  \mathbf {u}} \right )^\intercal 
]]></fr:tex>
                <html:p>
    We obtain the stationarity condition <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\frac {\partial  J}{\partial  \mathbf {u}} \equiv  0]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
